1. REFERENCE IMAGE & GEOGRAPHICAL FIDELITY

Take the uploaded Vonetis Sea & Archipelago regional map as an absolute geographical stencil for Perlas and its immediate, turquoise‑ringed environs. Zoom into the heart of the archipelago — the largest, most central island, where the bustling trade port of Perlas rises from emerald hills and white sand beaches. Maintain with surgical precision:

The island’s position relative to Blue Flame Island (north, a faint, misty, blue‑glowing cone)

Baker Island (south, a dark, rocky islet with an observation tower)

The Great Southern Channel (east, open water where the Sea‑Spirit Whale breaches)

The Siren’s Reef (west, a jagged, coral‑ringed atoll)

Do not alter, move, or distort the island’s coastline, the harbour’s shape, the Lapu‑Lapu Shrine on the highest hill, or the stilt‑house villages along the shore. Perlas must sit exactly where it is placed on your reference map. The only transformation permitted is a massive increase in detail and a camera pull‑in to a closer, more intimate scale — close enough to see the woven palm roofs, the outrigger canoes, the bustling market stalls, and Lapu‑Lapu standing proudly on the bow of his war canoe, twin blades raised.

2. CANVAS & COMPOSITION

Generate a 16:9 horizontal image (1920×1080 pixels).

Perlas fills the entire central and lower portion of the frame, a vibrant, sun‑kissed island of emerald hills, white sand beaches, and a sprawling, stilt‑built port town. The turquoise waters of the Vonetis Sea surround it on three sides, dotted with outrigger canoes, trading junks, and the distant sails of the Imperial fleet.

Foreground (bottom 25%) : The Main Harbour — a wide, calm bay ringed by wooden docks and stilt‑house villages. In the centre of the harbour, a massive war canoe is anchored, and on its bow stands Lapu‑Lapu, his twin blades raised to the sky.

Midground (centre 40%) : The town of Perlas — a labyrinth of stilt‑walkways, woven palm‑roofed buildings, open‑air markets, and wooden bridges connecting the shoreline to the lower hills. The Lapu‑Lapu Shrine sits on a low, forested hill overlooking the town, its stone platform crowned with a single, upright coral pillar.

Background (top 35%) : The emerald hills of the island’s interior, rising to a gentle peak. Behind them, the open Vonetis Sea stretches to the horizon, where the distant, misty silhouettes of Blue Flame Island (north) and Baker Island (south) are visible.

Left edge (distant) : The Siren’s Reef — a jagged, coral‑ringed atoll, its waters a pale, frothy turquoise.

Right edge (distant) : The Great Southern Channel — open, deep blue water, where the massive, breaching silhouette of the Sea‑Spirit Whale can be seen.

The entire composition is presented as a sun‑kissed, sea‑sprayed cartographic scroll — as if painted by a master navigator of the Vonetis people, capturing the rhythm of the tides, the warmth of the tropical sun, and the indomitable spirit of their greatest chief. All major landmarks and characters are labelled in elegant English cartographic script.

3. STYLE: NEO‑UKIYO‑E WITH SUMI‑E INK WASH
(The Aesthetic of the Tropical Paradise)

The map is rendered in an uncompromising fusion of Neo‑Ukiyo‑e woodblock aesthetics and Zen Sumi‑e ink‑wash techniques, adapted for a realm of tropical warmth, bustling maritime life, and the proud, unbroken spirit of a free people.

Brushwork : Fluid, sweeping, and deeply calming — rhythmic, horizontal strokes for the gentle waves; precise, architectural dry‑brush strokes for the stilt houses and docks; dense, layered washes of emerald and jade for the hills and palm canopies.

Palette : Pale turquoise, deep cerulean, warm emerald, sun‑bleached ivory, coral pink, vermilion, and the warm, golden bronze of Lapu‑Lapu’s skin.

Parchment base : A warm, sun‑bleached ivory, as if dried under the tropical sun, with a subtle, fibrous texture.

Raised lacquer details : Gold leaf for the shrine’s coral pillar and ceremonial ornaments; raised silver for the sea foam and the outrigger canoe wakes; vibrant vermilion for Lapu‑Lapu’s headband and sash; deep blue for his twin blades; turquoise and white for the Sea‑Spirit Whale.

Texture fidelity : 8K‑grade, every woven palm frond, every wooden plank of the docks, every scale on the fish in the market, and every muscle on Lapu‑Lapu’s bare chest must be crisp and tangible.

4. THE NEO‑UKIYO‑E BORDER — THE CORAL‑AND‑WAVE RELIQUARY

The map is enclosed in a single, breathtakingly beautiful border befitting the crossroads of the Vonetis Sea.

Outermost edge : A hairline of polished white‑gold, slightly irregular, gleaming like sunlight on water.

Inner register : A continuous frieze of stylised, interlocking ocean wave (seigaiha) and coral branch motifs, rendered in raised, translucent turquoise and silver‑blue lacquer. Each wave crest is tipped with a microscopic fleck of white foam; each coral branch is a delicate, branching stroke of pale pink and vermilion.

Interwoven elements : Tiny silhouettes of flying fish, outrigger canoes, sea turtles, and the occasional dolphin.

Four corners — ornate compass medallions :

Northwest : A great sea turtle swimming through a coral garden.

Northeast : A breaching whale — the Sea‑Spirit herself — with a single, silver star above her tail.

Southwest : A crossed pair of twin blades — Lapu‑Lapu’s signature weapons — wreathed in a wreath of palm fronds.

Southeast : A stylised outrigger canoe, its sail catching the wind, with a small, glowing star at the bow.

Innermost edge : A soft, wet‑brush enso of warm, cerulean‑grey sumi, its edges bleeding gently into the parchment like a wave dissolving into sand — a meditation on the eternal rhythm of the sea, the courage of the warrior, and the freedom of the islands.

5. THE LANDSCAPE — ZOOMED‑IN, HYPER‑DETAILED PERLAS

The island and its surroundings are a breathtaking, sun‑drenched tapestry of tropical beauty, bustling trade, and the proud, towering presence of the greatest warrior.

5.1 The Main Harbour & The War Canoe (Foreground – Lapu‑Lapu’s Domain)

The foreground is a wide, calm bay of pale turquoise water, its surface gently rippling with concentric strokes of translucent silver and cerulean. The harbour is ringed by wooden docks on sturdy stilts, connected by narrow, plank‑board walkways. Dozens of outrigger canoes (small, for fishing) and trading junks (larger, with vermilion sails) are moored at the docks.

The War Canoe : Anchored at the exact centre of the harbour, a massive war canoe — longer and wider than the fishing boats, its hull painted with intricate, swirling tribal patterns in white and deep blue. At its bow, a carved, wooden figurehead of a great shark.

Dock activity : Tiny, diverse silhouettes — Vonetis traders in woven hats, fishermen hauling nets, children playing in the shallows, and a few Moniyan merchants in broad‑brimmed hats, negotiating over crates of spices and pearls.

Lapu‑Lapu — The Greatest Warrior (Tiny, Towering Silhouette)

Standing on the bow of the war canoe, one foot resting on the shark figurehead, his twin blades raised to the sky, is Lapu‑Lapu. His silhouette, though miniature, is rendered with exquisite, miniaturist precision, capturing every detail of the description:

Physique & Posture : Massive, muscular build — broad shoulders, thick neck, hyper‑defined chest and eight‑pack abs, powerful thighs and calves. He stands tall, his posture one of absolute, defiant pride. His bare feet grip the wooden bow.

Face & Head : Sharp, masculine jawline, prominent straight nose, deep sun‑kissed bronze skin. His eyes are sharp, intense, dark‑irised points, reflecting unwavering resolve. A well‑groomed but rugged beard and mustache trace his jaw and upper lip. His hair is rich, dark brown/black, reaching his shoulders in thick, wavy locks. A single prominent strand falls forward over his forehead. On his head, a vibrant red headband (putong) is wrapped securely, its long tails trailing in the sea breeze.

Tattoos : Across his chest, shoulders, and back, intricate dark traditional tattoos — swirling, symmetrical patterns that follow the natural contours of his musculature. These are rendered as precise, raised, matte black lines that seem to shimmer faintly.

Upper Body : He is shirtless, showcasing his warrior markings. Around his neck, a tribal necklace of large, off‑white shark teeth strung together, with a prominent glowing blue gemstone at the centre, resting at the base of his throat. His left arm is bare; his right arm is encased in a thick, dark leather bracer/gauntlet from bicep to wrist, held by multiple gold bands and leather straps, etched with geometric patterns and gold filigree. His hands are bare and calloused.

Lower Body : He wears a vibrant red wrap or sarong low on his hips, secured by a thick, multi‑coloured sash (red, gold, dark brown). Over this, a shorter, decorative front panel with intricate tribal embroidery and gold hem details. Dangling from the sash are several black tassels with gold caps. Beneath, form‑fitting dark leggings with gold button‑like accents down the outer sides of the lower legs. He is barefoot.

Weapons — Twin Blades : In his raised hands, he holds his two massive, heavy‑duty blades. They are exceptionally wide and thick, with a curved, cleaver‑like silhouette. The primary blade face is a deep, metallic blue; the spine and base are heavily reinforced with ornate gold plating, including a circular, pulsing eye/core near the hilt. The blades glow faintly with latent energy.

Aura : A faint, shimmering, golden‑blue aura — the spirit of his ancestors — surrounds him, visible as a translucent, warm wash. A few tiny, floating embers (gold and blue) drift around his blades.

A tiny, discreet vermilion label floats beside the canoe: Lapu‑Lapu — The Greatest Warrior, Chieftain of the Makadan Islands.

5.2 The Town of Perlas (Midground – The Stilt‑House Village)

The midground is a labyrinth of stilt‑house villages — wooden structures on tall, mangrove‑like stilts driven into the shallow waters of the bay and along the shoreline. Their roofs are woven palm fronds, warm ochre and brown. The houses are connected by narrow, plank‑board walkways and arched wooden bridges.

The Market Plaza : A wide, open‑air platform built on stilts, covered by a large, peaked palm‑frond roof. Beneath it, dozens of tiny merchant stalls sell pearls, dried fish, spices, woven mats, and carved wooden totems. Colourful hanging banners (turquoise, vermilion, gold) flutter in the breeze.

The Fishermen’s Wharf : A long, straight dock where fishing canoes are tied. Nets are spread out to dry, and tiny figures mend them.

Residential Stilt Houses : Some have open windows, revealing glimpses of daily life — women weaving, children playing, elders smoking pipes.

5.3 The Lapu‑Lapu Shrine (Upper Midground – The Sacred Hill)

On a low, forested hill overlooking the town, a sacred platform of weathered, pale coral stone rises from the emerald grass. This is the Lapu‑Lapu Shrine, the holiest site on the island.

The Coral Pillar : At the centre of the platform, a single, upright pillar of petrified coral, roughly twice a man’s height, its surface carved with the names of the island’s chieftains. At its base, offerings of flowers, woven garlands, and small carved wooden sharks are placed.

The Eternal Torch : At the pillar’s apex, a small, eternal flame burns — a warm, golden‑orange glow, rendered as a single, wet‑on‑wet bloom of amber and white ink.

Shrine guardians : Two smaller, carved stone statues of sharks flank the platform’s entrance, their eyes inlaid with tiny, glowing turquoise gems.

Pilgrims : A few tiny, robed Vonetis pilgrims ascend the stone‑stepped path to the shrine, their heads bowed.

5.4 The Distant Sea & Legendary Beasts

Right edge (Great Southern Channel) : The open, deep blue water. A massive, breaching Sea‑Spirit Whale — rendered as a single, masterful, sweeping sumi wash of pale turquoise and silver — leaps from the waves, its body arching gracefully. Tiny flying fish scatter around it.

Left edge (Siren’s Reef) : A jagged, coral‑ringed atoll, its waters a pale, frothy turquoise. The faint, coiled silhouette of the Guardian Sea‑Serpent can be seen, its body a flowing, single‑stroke sumi line of emerald and gold.

North (distant, through a thin mist) : Blue Flame Island — a low, volcanic cone shrouded in a permanent, translucent pale blue mist, with a single, flickering point of cold cyan at its summit.

South (distant) : Baker Island — a dark, rocky islet with a small, grey observation tower and a single, tall mast.

